We recommended to the Management to:

Through the Municipal Accountant, to demand in writing the immediate liquidation of fund transfer granted to various barangays by setting specific timeline to be complied;
Verify the absence of any Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) for these projects. If proven to be none, provide a certification signed by both the Municipal Mayor and the Barangay Captain that no MOA was prepared relative to these projects;
For future fund transfers to implementing agencies, ensure that a MOA was prepared to provide for the requirements for the project implementation and reporting; and 
Assign a personnel responsible in monitoring compliance with the terms and conditions in the MOA as well as validation of actual accomplishments vis-à-vis purpose for which the fund transfer was granted.

We recommended to the Mayor through the Accounting Unit: 

To fully adhere with Section 1 and 1.2 of COA Circular 2012-001;
To strengthen internal control in the granting of Cash Advances to avoid unliquidated Cash advances at year end which shall include but not limited to establishing cash advance cut-offs on December, monitoring those with previously unsettled balances and prohibiting them from drawing new cash advances unless prior CAs are already settled;
In the event cash advance cut-offs for December could not be implemented, set up working fund in an amount solely for the purpose of Kuyamis Activities;
To prohibit delayed cash advance settlements such as partial liquidations, immediate liquidation shall be demanded; and
To enforce immediate settlement of unliquidated cash advances within fifteen calendar days from receipt of this AOM. Non-settlement by respective accountable officers will constitute application of Item 9.0 of COA Circular 2012-004.

We recommended to the Management to:

Discourage practice of procuring items beforehand then processing for reimbursement thereof and instead, implement the procurement procedures laid out in RA 9184 and its Revised Implementing Rules and Regulation; 
Improve its procurement procedures by properly identifying needed items and managing its timeline to ensure ample time for the procurement activities;

 Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly evaluate the requests for reimbursements submitted to ensure that only valid requests will be processed.

We recommended the Management to:

For the alternate books received:

a)	Cancel the Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) and issue an Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) instead, indicating the actual books received;

b)	Discontinue the practice of receiving replacements in lieu of unavailable stocks. Instead, prepare another purchase request to check availability in other suppliers or review the specifications of the books for possible modifications;

For the procurement through Direct Contracting:

c)	Strictly monitor compliance to the requirements of other oversight agencies, such as Commission on Higher Education, to improve planning and execution activities and to give ample time for the conduct of applicable procurement method; 

d)	Procure through Competitive Bidding for purchases of more than ₱100,000 as required for a 4th Class Municipality; and 

e)	Should management opt for Direct Contracting, ensure the compliance to the requirements as stated in the 2016 Revised IRR of the Republic Act No. 9184.

We recommended that Management:

Ensure completeness and propriety of the required supporting documents for all contracts submitted to COA for review in accordance with COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 and COA Circular 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009;

Require the personnel in-charge in the submission of the contracts and its supporting documents to maintain a checklist of required documents for each of the transactions to serve as a guide to ensure the completeness of the documents submitted to COA for review;

Employ means to ensure timely submission to COA of any POs or contracts entered into by the Municipality to suppliers.

